init_text:
How Worried Should We Be About Screen Time During the Pandemic?

The coronavirus pandemic ended the screen time debate: Screens won. We all now find ourselves on our screens for school, for work and for connecting with family and friends during this time of social distancing and increased isolation.

But should we be worried about this excessive screen use right now? Or should we finally get over it and embrace the benefits of our digital devices?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The real problem isn't the time that kids spend on their smart phones, tablets or computer screens.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: We saw with this pandemic and the way society responded that most parents did not have a sufficient amount of control over how their children could use

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: These networks have digital stores, simulated cities that are part of multiplayer games, and have access to an online news station that keeps kids up with current events

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It's time to begin talking about the opposite of screen time, which is life time.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The more that kids use their screen devices, the less time they have for human contact and interaction in the real world.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Unfortunately, the need for physical interaction pressures anyone that doesn't have a lot of friends to begin craving more and more screen time.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Humans have a natural need for human contact and all of us, kids and adults, need the real world interaction even-more during stressful times like this

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The real world is where life occurs.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The screen world can be a really fun place, and there's a lot to learn, but it's not so very different than any other addiction.
